50|$|Six brick built kilns were {{identified}} {{during the course}} of the excavations. All were fragmentary and truncated by both the modern buildings and later 19th century buildings. All that survived of each was the partial remains of circular structures forming the base of the pottery-firing kiln. A number of rectangular <b>ash</b> <b>pits,</b> evenly spaced along the edges of the main kiln bases, {{were identified}} with each kiln. These contained ash and kiln furniture and were used to collect the burnt material falling from the fires above. Surrounding each of the kilns were cobbled floors, which sloped downward to the external edges of the <b>ash</b> <b>pits</b> - to allow easy emptying of the content of the <b>ash</b> <b>pits.</b>|$|R
